CRIMEAN-CONGO HEMORRHAGIC FEVER: BACKGROUND
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 27 Feb 2015
From: Jan Clement <jan.clement@uzleuven.be> [edited]


The story of the name "CCHF" is even a bit more complicated, and has in fact a strong diplomatic, former Cold War flavor.

"Crimean haemorrhagic fever (CHF)" was first observed and clinically detailed in 200 Russian soldiers, appointed in 1944 by the Russian authorities to harvest crops during wartime in the Crimea, instead of the local peasants. However, due to this unexpected and previously non-scheduled military activity, these soldiers had to sleep outdoors, were thereby heavily bitten by ticks, and suffered shortly afterwards a mostly severe and hemorrhagic feverish condition, thus described for the 1st time as "CHF". In 1945, inoculation in "volunteers" of filtered suspensions of ticks and tissues of these CHF patients proved that CHF was caused indeed by a tick-transmitted virus. Nevertheless, proper isolation of this CHF-virus (CHFV) failed during following years, until it finally succeeded in June 1967 in the lab of the renowned Russian virologist Mikhael Chumakov, from a fatal case, that occurred, however, not in the Crimea, but in Samarkand (nowadays Uzbekistan), far away from the Crimea [1].

However, a then unknown "new" virus, prospectively named V3010, had been isolated already in 1956 by the Belgian infectiologist Dr Ghislaine Courtois from a febrile child in Stanleyville (now Kisangani, [Democratic Republic of the Congo], in the former Belgian Congo). In following decades, evidence for the presence of V3010, later renamed as "Congo virus", was found in Greece, Portugal, South-Africa, Madagascar, the Maghreb, Dubai, Saudi-Arabia, Kuwait and Iraq [2, 3].

In February 1967, Congo virus was sent by these western virologists to Rockefeller Foundation Virus Laboratory (RFVL) in New York, and found to be identical only to another Congo virus strain from Uganda, but not to any other named virus at that time. Chumakov sent his Russian strain only later to RFVL, where it was proved to be entirely identical to Congo virus [4].

The International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses [ICTV] thus proposed in 1969 the name "Congo-Crimean hemorrhagic fever virus", but the Russians kept insisting on "Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus". After a long diplomatic standstill, and against all principles of scientific nomenclature based on priority of publication and of virus isolation, this was finally adopted as the official denomination in 1973, in possibly the 1st instance of a virus losing its name to politics and the Cold War.

An appropriate and diplomatic "solution" to this still awkward situation is using preferentially the now prevalent abbreviation "CCHF(V)", where it is left to the beliefs and devotion of the user to interpret which "C" is which. It goes without saying which solution of this little riddle is mostly applied nowadays in ... Belgium.

References
----------
1. Chumakov MP, Butenko AM, Shalunova NV, et al (May-June 1968): New data on the viral agent of Crimean hemorrhagic fever. Vopr Virusol (in Russian) 13(3): 377.
2. Simpson DI, Knight EM, Courtois G, et al (February 1967): Congo virus: a hitherto undescribed virus occurring in Africa. I. Human isolations -- clinical notes. East Afr Med J 44(2): 86-92
3. Woodall JP, Williams MC, Simpson DI (February 1967): Congo virus: a hitherto undescribed virus occurring in Africa. II. Identification studies. East Afr Med J 44(2): 93-8.
4. Casals J (May 1969): Antigenic similarity between the virus causing Crimean hemorrhagic fever and Congo virus. Proc Soc Exp Biol Med 131 (1): 233-6. doi:10.3181/00379727-131-33847

