Date: Sun 8 Mar 2015
From: Jack Woodall <promed@promedmail.org> [edited]


I joined the East African Virus Research Institute in Entebbe, Uganda in 1965 with a PhD in entomology and virology. The 2 virologists on the staff were backlogged, so the director asked me to dig out some deep-frozen samples of mouse brains containing unidentified viruses that had been sent to us for identification and work them up.

I inoculated V3010, which had been in the Revco at -70 deg C [-94 deg F] for many years, into 2-day-old mice and got the virus (no PPE, mouth pipetting, no masks or gloves in those days!), cross-tested it by HI [hemagglutination inhibition] and CF [complement fixation] against everything in our virus library and it came up negative, so I sent it to Jordi Casals at RF [Rockefeller Foundation] New York, who said it was new. I asked Courtois what he wanted to name it and he said "Congo virus", so that is how I published it.

In 1967 I had moved to be director of the Rockefeller Foundation's Virus Laboratory Belem, Brazil, and hosted 3 young virologists from Chumakov's lab, where they had been trying isolation in weanling mice. They saw that we were isolating a lot of new viruses from mosquitoes, people, and wildlife by inoculating newborn rather than 21-day-old mice, which had been the Rockefeller routine since yellow fever research days. When they got back to their lab in Moscow, they took out their CCHF samples and put them in newborns, and bingo! they got the virus. They then sent their virus to Casals and were chagrined to find that it was identical to Congo virus.

All this is in chapter 3 "Personal reflections" in the Ergonul & Whitehouse book Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever, which you [Jan Clement] have obviously read!

--
Jack Woodall (Mod.JW)
Associate Editor, ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is interesting to have the complete CCHF history summarized in one place in this ProMED-mail post. ProMED thanks Jan Clement and his colleague for their contribution, and Mod.JW for the account of his historical involvement in the isolation of CCHF virus in Uganda. The debate for using Crimea or Congo first when discussing CCHF virus and the disease persists in many quarters. The good historical news is that there was scientific communication and collaboration going on between Russian and western scientists despite the international cold war tensions at the time.

CCHF remains a public health problem in many parts of the world, with cases reported this year (2015) -- see ProMED posts listed below. Since many viruses know nothing of international boundaries, as amply illustrated by CCHF, international communication and collaboration are still needed. - Mod.TY]
